1276","1317":"1317","Longford, Derbyshire, England":"Longford, Derbyshire, England","Dsp, , , England":"England, United Kingdom","Norfolk, England":"Norfolk, England","Maxstoke Castle, Warwickshire, England":"Maxstoke Castle, Warwickshire, England","England":"England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Ida","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a Norman name, of Germanic origin, derived from <i>īd</i> ‘work’. This died out during the later Middle Ages. It was revived in the 19th century, influenced by its use in  Tennyson's  The Princess (  1847 ) for the central character, who devotes herself to the cause of women's rights and women's education in a thoroughly Victorian way. The name is also associated with Mount Ida in Crete, which was connected in classical times with the worship of Zeus, king of the gods, who was supposed to have been brought up in a cave on the mountainside. In the 1930s it became famous as the name of the film star  Ida Lupino  (  1914–1995 )."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705190,"age":20,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705191,"age":45,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When Ida Oddingsells was born in 1270, in Norfolk, England, her father, Sir William de Odingsells II, was 25 and her mother, Ela LONGESPEE, was 53. She had at least 2 sons and 3 daughters with Sir Roger de Herdeburgh II. She died on 1 March 1321, at the a